				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				First off, it's great that they shut down the public aspect.  Censorship?  I don't think so.  After all, you can whine to your heart's content on any one or more of the other boards out there (like Everlore and Caster's Realm for example), so people's ability to complain about how horrible Verant is, and how horrible Everquest, has not been stifled in the least.  In FACT, the increased anonymity of not using your &quot;Station ID&quot; to post your poorly-thought-out gripes actually FREES you pissy whiners from having to worry about having your account suspended/banned for showing your asses.<BR>
<BR>
Furthermore, I think I know what the final straw was.  I counted THREE threads complaining about the changes to the Singing Steel Boots and Greaves, a change which was begged for by the majority of bards for a LONG time!  This on top of the fact that there were people who made it their business to parse and ridicule everything that Verant said (several messages, for example, that went step by step managing to complain about every single item listed in the patch message).<BR>
<BR>
I would submit that Verant employees were probably the people Verant was trying to protect by taking this action, more than the players.  How disheartening would it be to work your butt off trying to fix/improve something FOR the players, only to be jumped on by the raging iceholes who believe that Verant can do nothing right, and on YOUR OWN COMPANY'S WEBSITE!!!!<BR>
<BR>
Believe me, future MMOGs will, if they meet with any success, experience the same problems, simply because these grief posters will go and play the game, if only to be able to find things to complain about.<BR>
<BR>
Goodbye Official Message Board.  It could have been good, but it just wasn't going to happen again.
